04914nam a22005775i 9781554581177DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20062004xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97815545811777 a10.51644/97815545811772doi  a(DE-B1597)667590  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBR195.J8 M87 2006 7aREL0150002bisacsh04a270.11 aMurray, Michele, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPlaying a Jewish Game :bGentile Christian Judaizing in the First and Second Centuries CE /cMichele Murray. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Christianity and Judaism ;v1300tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tMap of Syria -- tIntroduction: Judaizing and the Early Development of Christianity -- tGentile Attraction to Judaism in the Roman Empire -- tChristian Judaizing in Galatia: Paul’s Letter to the Galatians -- tChristian Judaizing in Syria: Barnabas, the Didache, and Pseudo-Clementine Literature -- tChristian Judaizing in Asia Minor: Revelation, Ignatius, and Justin Martyr -- tMarcion and Melito: More Evidence of Christian Judaizing in Asia Minor? -- tConclusion: Christian Judaizing and the Forging of a Distinct Christian Identity -- tScholarly Perceptions of Jewish-Christian Relations in Antiquity -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tAncient Sources Index -- tSubject Index -- tSeries Published by Wilfrid Laurier University0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIs it possible that early Christian anti-Judaism was directed toward people other than Jews? Michele Murray proposes that significant strands of early Christian anti-Judaism were directed against Gentile Christians. More specifically, it was directed toward Gentile Christian judaizers. These were Christians who combined a commitment to Christianity with adherence in varying degrees to Jewish practices, without viewing such behaviour as contradictory. Several Christian leaders thought that these community members dangerously blurred the boundaries between Christianity and Judaism. As such, Gentile Christian judaizers became the target of much anti-Jewish rhetoric in various early Christian writings. Evidence of Gentile Christian judaizers can be found in canonical sources, such as Pauls Letter to the Galatians and the Book of Revelation, as well as non-canonical sources, such as the Epistle of Barnabas, the Didache, and Justin Martyr’s Dialogue with Trypho. In order to compare the phenomenon of judaizing and the reaction to it of ecclesiastical authorities, Murray organizes the evidence by probable geographical location, using Asia Minor and Syria as the two main loci. The phenomenon of Gentile Christian judaizing is examined within the broader context of Jewish-Christian relations in the early centuries, and is the first attempt to draw all possible references to Gentile Christian judaizers together into one study to consider them as a whole. This discussion invites readers to reflect on the existence of Gentile Christian judaizers as another point on the continuum of Jewish-Christian relations in the Greco-Roman world — an area, Murray concludes, that needs to be more carefully defined.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristianity and other religionsxJudaism. 0aChurch historyyPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 0aJudaismxRelationsxChristianity. 4aHistory. 4aHistory: Jewish Studies. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package p